05010nam a22008055i 9780674062931DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1041187648  a(OCoLC)840438790  a97806740629317 a10.4159/harvard.97806740629312doi  a(DE-B1597)178290  a(OCoLC)777264540  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aJC421b.B52 2012eb 7aPOL0070002bisacsh04a321.82231 aBilakovics, Steven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocracy without Politics /cSteven Bilakovics. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. “More than Kings yet Less than Men” -- tChapter 2. Civilization without the Discontents -- tChapter 3. The Regime of Revolution -- tChapter 4. Political Phoenix -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Western democracies today, politics and politicians are held in contempt by the majority of citizens. Steven Bilakovics argues that this disdain of politics follows neither from the discontents of our liberal political system nor from the preoccupations of a consumer society. Rather, extending Tocqueville’s analysis of the modern democratic way of life, he traces the sources of political cynicism to democracy itself. Democratic society’s defining openness—its promise of transcendent freedom and unlimited power—renders the everyday politics of argument and persuasion absurd by comparison. Persuasion is devalued relative to the norms of free-market competition and patriotic community, assertions of self-interest and self-expression take the place of arguing together, and political life is diminished by the absence of mediating talk. Bilakovics identifies this trend across the political landscape—in the clashing authenticities of the ";culture war,"; the perennial pursuit of the political outsider to set things right again, the call for a postpartisan politics, rising demands on government alongside falling expectations of what government can do, and in a political rhetoric that is at once petty and hyperbolic. To reform democratic politics and ameliorate its pathologies, Bilakovics calls on us to overcome our anti-political prejudice and rethink robust democracy as the citizen's practice of persuading and being persuaded in turn.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracyxHistory. 0aDemocracyxPhilosophyxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2012z9783110288995oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE HISTORY; POLITICAL SCIENCE, SOCIOLOGY  2012z978311029371508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET GESCHICHTE, POLITIKWISS., SOZIOLOGIE  2012z9783110288971oZDB-23-DPS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067406293140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674062931423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674062931.jpg  a978-3-11-029371-5  E-BOOK PACKAGE HISTORY; POLITICAL SCIENCE, SOCIOLOGY  2012b2012  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN 